In 2013, government health officials undertook activities to support a clinic providing post-abortion care for women in the eastern region of Guinea-Bissau – a step in the journey to making safe abortion care accessible to women in the country. Others on the ground in Guinea-Bissau, like the network of young francophone activists working with IPAS to advance women’s reproductive health and rights in the country, need assistance to help make abortion safe. In five countries – DRC, Kenya, Malawi, South Africa, Uganda – women throughout DRC take part in routine meetings hosted by IPAS Africa and local partners to discuss their access to abortion and family planning services. It is the only forum offered in the DRC where women can speak openly about their needs – and receive needed reproductive health and rights education – without fear of censure or reprisal.
Project Regulatory reform to increase safe abortion service provision in the DRC Granting registered nurses in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) the authority to counsel, prescribe, and distribute medication abortion, promotes women’s well-being and contributes to the growth of women’s human rights in the region. Termed “community midwives”, this cadre of health care workers frees up clinic staff to dedicate more time to counseling and conducting medical consultations.
